From February 1992 until March 1993, [[Colombia]] suffered [[rolling blackout]]s of up to 10 hours a day due to a particularly strong [[El Niño]] season, which dried the reservoirs in hydroelectric plants in a country deriving 70% of its energy output from hydroelectric sources; consequently, the government decided to use DST to help save electricity. The experiment failed to deliver the intended results, possibly due to Colombia's low latitude, and the DST experiment was discontinued.<ref>{{Cite web|author= |url=http://www.timeanddate.com/worldclock/timezone.html?n=41&syear=1990|title=Time zone changes and daylight saving time start/end dates between year 1990 and 1999 - Bogota, Colombia |publisher=timeanddate.com |accessdate=2008-05-09}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Daylight saving time by country]] *[[1992 Colombian energy crisis]]
