{{Infobox person |name= Frank Merry Stenton |image=Frank Merry Stenton.jpg |image_size=200px |caption= |birth_name= |birth_date= {{birth date|1880|5|17|df=yes}} |birth_place= [[Manchester]], England |residence= |spouse= [[Doris Mary Stenton]] |death_date= {{death date and age|1967|9|15|1880|5|17|df=yes}} |death_place= |resting_place= |nationality= [[England|English]] |known_for= |education= |alma_mater= |occupation= Historian }}
'''Sir Frank Merry Stenton''' (17 May 1880 – 15 September 1967) was a 20th-century historian of [[Anglo-Saxon England]], and president of the [[Royal Historical Society]] (1937–1945).<ref>[http://www.history.ac.uk/makinghistory/historians/stenton_frank.html Institute of Historical Research, Summary]; [http://www.royalhistoricalsociety.org/aboutus.htm Royal Historical Society, 'About Us'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209163942/http://www.royalhistoricalsociety.org/aboutus.htm |date=2010-02-09 }}. Retrieved 19 February 2010.</ref>
He was educated at [[Keble College, Oxford]], and was elected an [[Oxbridge Fellow|Honorary Fellow]] in 1947.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Keble College Centenary Register 1870–1970 |editor=Drennan, Basil St G.|year=1970|publisher=Keble College, Oxford|isbn=978-0-85033-048-9|page=3}}</ref>
He was the author of ''Anglo-Saxon England'', a volume of the [[Oxford History of England]], first published in 1943 and widely considered a classic history of the period. He delivered the [[Ford Lectures]] at [[Oxford University]] in 1929.
Stenton was a professor of history at the [[University of Reading]] (1926–1946), and subsequently the university's vice-chancellor (1946–1950). During his period as vice-chancellor at Reading, he presided over the university's purchase of [[Whiteknights Park]], creating the new campus that allowed for the expansion of the university in later decades. In November 2008, it was announced that a new hall of residence to be constructed on that campus would be named Stenton Hall, in his honour.<ref name=frankstent>{{cite web | url = http://www.reading.ac.uk/bulletin/pdfs/489.pdf | title = University of Reading Bulletin (20 November 2008) | publisher = University of Reading | page = 3 | accessdate = 2008-11-20}}</ref>{{dead link|date=May 2018}} The annual Stenton Lecture, given by an eminent historian, was inaugurated at Reading University in 1967.<ref name=Reading_Uni>{{cite web |title=Stenton Lecture |website=University of Reading, Dept. of History |url=https://www.reading.ac.uk/history/research/hist-stentonlectures.aspx |accessdate=4 May 2018 }}</ref>
He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[1948 New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38161 |supp=y|page=2|date=30 December 1947}}</ref> and received the [[accolade]] from [[George VI of the United Kingdom|King George VI]] at Buckingham Palace on 10 February 1948.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38207|pages=1035–1036|date=13 February 1948}}</ref>
His wife, [[Doris Mary Stenton]], wrote a preface to the third edition of ''Anglo-Saxon England'', published after his death, and edited ''Preparatory to Anglo-Saxon England Being the Collected Papers of Frank Merry Stenton'', published in 1970. She was an historian in her own right, producing ''English Society in the Early Middle Ages'' for the [[Pelican Books|Pelican]] History of England, and ''The English Woman in History'' (1957).<ref name=Reading_Uni />
Stenton's papers, together with those of his wife Lady Doris Stenton, their library and his coin collection are part of the special collections at Reading University.
