{{PoliGeoSubfoot}}

The suburbs of [[Perth (suburb)|Perth]] and [[Northbridge, Western Australia|Northbridge]] were combined until 1982 when Northbridge was established as a separate suburb.<ref name=landinfo>{{LandInfo WA|m|N|2008-08-31}}</ref>
==Streets starting with A or B == {| class="wikitable sortable" |- !Name !class="unsortable"|Suburb !class="unsortable"|Date built !class="unsortable"|Name source !class="unsortable"|Other name(s) !class="unsortable"|Notes !class="unsortable"|Image |- |[[Aberdeen Road, Perth|Aberdeen Road]] |Perth |By 1838 |[[George Hamilton-Gordon, 4th Earl of Aberdeen]] | |The Aberdeen of Aberdeen Street was that Earl of Aberdeen who was Foreign Secretary in the Duke of Wellington's Cabinet when Western Australia was founded...His name first appeared in Aberdeen-road, East Perth, where it can be seen on the first street map of Perth issued in 1838; but a later survey by Roe of this part of the town wiped out that thoroughfare, and his name was transferred to the present Aberdeen-street running off Beaufort-street.<ref name=aberdeenofaberdeen>{{cite web|title=Perth Names. Aberdeen of Aberdeen Street|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/46285603|publisher=The West Australian|accessdate=21 May 2018|date=17 December 1938}}</ref> | |- |[[Aberdeen Street, Perth]] |Perth, Northbridge (Fitzgerald to William Street) |August–September 1829 |[[George Hamilton-Gordon, 4th Earl of Aberdeen]] |Duke Street, Lamb Street, Short Street |The Aberdeen of Aberdeen Street was that Earl of Aberdeen who was Foreign Secretary in the Duke of Wellington's Cabinet when Western Australia was founded.<ref name=aberdeenofaberdeen /> |[[File:OIC_street_sign_perth_Aberdeen_St.jpg|100px]] |- |[[Adelaide Terrace]] |Perth, East Perth |1830 |[[Queen Adelaide of the United Kingdom|Queen Adelaide]] | |Named after Queen Adelaide, "the ruling sovereign" at the time of Perth's founding. The wife of King William IV.<ref name=streetsofperth>{{cite web|title=Streets of Perth. Origin of Their Names|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/37661804|publisher=Western Mail|accessdate=14 May 2018|date=10 November 1927}}</ref> |[[File:Adelaide_Terrace_high-up_sign_May_2013.jpg|100px]] |- |Amy Street |Perth |after 1855 | | | | |- |Antonas Road |Northbridge |after 1979 | | | | |- |Aria Lane |Perth, Highgate |after 1855 | | | | |- |[[Astone Lane]] |Perth |2006 |[[Antonino Astone]] | |"During that time, being more significant, Mr Astone held the first license to transport passengers to and from the Fremantle Port. Mr Astone transported hundreds of migrants and brought them to settle within the Northbridge area. During the 1950s, Mr Astone made a significant contribution to the local community through his work as the owner of a taxi fleet, fruit and vegetable vendor, and a crockery business where he established a vast network of Northbridge restaurant clients. His crockery business continued for 26 years. My father was a well known figure within the Northbridge community, who resided at 135 Bulwer Street for over 40 years. The cohort of students from that time (Highgate Primary School) remember Mr Astone as the 'Man with the red truck'."<ref>{{cite web|title=Ordinary Meeting of Council - 26 September 2006|url=https://www.vincent.wa.gov.au/Profiles/vincent/assets/moduledata/councilmeetings/8e6a2288-444f-4cac-ac44-cdf91defd1c4/1.0/20060926.pdf|publisher=City of Vincent|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> | |- |[[Baker Avenue]] |Perth | |Henry Baker - City Baker | |Henry Baker was a carrier...Mr Baker investigated in several properties. Hence, Baker Avenue remains alongside Birdwood Square between Bulwer Street and Brisbane Street. Soon, he was making bread in the more literal sense and for the next 60 years his horse-drawn baker's carts were making home deliveries of bread to the Highgate area, bearing the legend H. Baker, City Baker.<ref name=mtlawleysociety>{{cite web|title=Our Heritage News|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/53d1c638e4b04e06965de70c/t/592e309ae6f2e11e077d2e4e/1496199344368/Heritage%2C+Mount+Lawley+Society++Vol+40+1-2017.pdf|publisher=Mount Lawley Society|accessdate=21 May 2018|date=April 2017}}</ref> | |- |Barclay Street |Perth |1893 | |Now Elder Street | | |-